  <p>The most consequential number at a World Cup is not always a scoreline. On June 17, 2026, Kylian Mbappé scored twice in France's 3-1 defeat of Senegal, overtaking Olivier Giroud to become the leading goalscorer in French football history. By the final whistle a quieter milestone had landed on the betting board: France's price to lift the trophy had been cut to roughly +400, its shortest since the futures opened back in December, and enough to leave it standing alone at the top — clear of Spain at around +500 and England near +700. The defending-era contenders had not gone anywhere. The market had simply decided to point.</p>

  <p>We do not publish tips or picks, and this is not one. But the moment a sprawling field of hopefuls compresses into a single short-priced favorite is one of the most useful — and least understood — things a betting market does. Because when the favorite shrinks, the arithmetic underneath every wager on it changes, and almost none of that change is in the bettor's favor.</p>

