  <h2>What a shrinking favorite actually means</h2>

  <p>Start with the price. In American odds, +400 means a winning 100 stake returns 400 in profit. Converted to a probability — the market's estimate of how likely the outcome is — that is 100 ÷ (400 + 100) = 0.20, or 20%. Before Mbappé's brace, France was drifting around +500 to +600, an implied 15-17%. The repricing to +400 is the market lifting France's modelled chance of winning the whole tournament to about one in five, and lifting it above every rival at once. If you want to run that conversion on any price yourself, our <a href="/tools/betting-odds-calculator">betting odds and implied-probability calculator</a> does it instantly — and shows the slice the headline number hides.</p>

  <p>That slice matters more here than almost anywhere else. Implied probabilities across a full outright market — every team that can win — always sum to well over 100%. The surplus is the bookmaker's margin, and on a futures board with dozens of runners it is unusually fat, often 20% or more in aggregate. So France's "20%" is an overstatement: strip out the house's cut and the fair number is meaningfully lower. The shorter the favorite, the more that fixed percentage margin weighs on a payout that is already thin.</p>

